Laravel API Code Generation Guidelines
When generating Laravel API code for this project, follow these conventions and patterns:
File Structure & Naming Conventions
Base Classes
• BaseModel: app/Models/BaseModel.php - Abstract base class for all models
• BaseFormRequest: app/Http/Requests/BaseFormRequest.php - Base class for all form requests
Controllers
• Location: app/Http/Controllers/Api
• Naming: {Resource}Controller.php (e.g., TaskController.php)
• Class name: {Resource}Controller (PascalCase)
Form Requests
• Location: app/Http/Requests/{Resource}/
• Naming: {Resource}{Method}Request.php (e.g., TaskPostRequest.php, TaskPutRequest.php)
• Class name: {Resource}{Method}Request
• Must extend: App\Http\Requests\BaseFormRequest
Services
• Location: app/Services/{Resource}/
• Naming: {Action}{Resource}.php (e.g., CreateTask.php, UpdateTask.php)
• Class name: {Action}{Resource} (PascalCase, verb + noun)
• Single method: handle() that takes data and returns the model
Models
• Location: app/Models/
• Naming: {Resource}.php (singular, PascalCase)
• Class name: {Resource} (singular)
• Must extend: App\Models\BaseModel
API Resources
• Location: app/Http/Resources/
• Naming: {Resource}Resource.php (e.g., TaskResource.php)
• Class name: {Resource}Resource
Enums
• Location: app/Enums/Models/
• Naming: {Resource}ModelEnum.php (e.g., TaskModelEnum.php)
• Class name: {Resource}ModelEnum
• Type: Backed enum with string values
Migrations
• Use enum constants for all field names (never hardcode strings)
Coding Style
Naming Conventions
• Classes: PascalCase (e.g., TaskController, CreateTask, BaseModel)
• Methods: camelCase (e.g., handle(), authorize(), rules(), modelEnum())
• Variables: camelCase (e.g., $task, $tasks, $data, $mappedData)
• Enum cases: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (e.g., TABLE_NAME, IS_COMPLETED, CREATED_AT)
• Database fields: snake_case (e.g., is_completed, created_at)
• API response fields: camelCase (e.g., isCompleted, createdAt)
Code Organization
• Use dependency injection in controllers for services
• Keep controllers thin - delegate business logic to services
• Services are single-action classes with one handle() method
• All string literals (field names, table names) must come from enums
Architecture Patterns
BaseModel Pattern (Required)
All models must extend App\Models\BaseModel which:
• Extends Eloquent's Model class
• Requires child classes to implement modelEnum() method
• Automatically sets table and fillable properties from the enum in the constructor
Enum Pattern (Required)
Every model must have a corresponding enum in app/Enums/Models/{Resource}ModelEnum.php with:
1. Enum cases for:
• TABLE_NAME - table name
• Field names (e.g., TITLE, DESCRIPTION, IS_COMPLETED, CREATED_AT, UPDATED_AT)
• Client field names if different (e.g., CLIENT_IS_COMPLETED = 'isCompleted')
2. Static methods for each field:
   public static function title(): string
   {
       return self::TITLE->value;
   }
3. Helper methods:
• tableName(): string - returns table name
• fillable(): array - returns array of fillable fields
• fieldMapping(): array - returns mapping from client field names to backend field names
Model Pattern
Models must extend BaseModel and implement modelEnum():
class {Resource} extends BaseModel
{
    /**
     * Get the model enum class name.
     * 
     * @return string
     */
    protected static function modelEnum(): string
    {
        return {Resource}ModelEnum::class;
    }
}
Important: Models should NOT have their own constructor. The BaseModel constructor handles setting table and fillable from the enum automatically.
Form Request Pattern
1. Extend App\Http\Requests\BaseFormRequest
2. Use enum methods in rules() method (never hardcode field names):
   return [
       {Resource}ModelEnum::title() => 'required|string|max:255',
   ];
3. Implement fieldMapping() method that returns {Resource}ModelEnum::fieldMapping()
4. Include messages() method using enum methods for custom validation messages:
   public function messages(): array
   {
       return [
           {Resource}ModelEnum::title() . '.required' => 'Title is required.',
       ];
   }
Service Pattern
Services are single-action classes:
class Create{Resource}
{
    public function handle(array $data): {Resource} {
        ${resource} = {Resource}::create($data);
        return ${resource};
    }
}
Controller Pattern
Controllers are thin and use dependency injection:
public function store({Resource}PostRequest $request, Create{Resource} $create{Resource})
{
    ${resource} = $create{Resource}->handle($request->validated());
    return new {Resource}Resource(${resource});
}
For delete operations, return response()->noContent().
API Resource Pattern
Use enum methods to get attributes, return camelCase for client:
public function toArray(Request $request): array
{
    return [
        'id' => $this->id,
        'title' => $this->getAttribute({Resource}ModelEnum::title()),
        'isCompleted' => $this->getAttribute({Resource}ModelEnum::isCompleted()),
        'createdAt' => $this->getAttribute({Resource}ModelEnum::createdAt()),
        'updatedAt' => $this->getAttribute({Resource}ModelEnum::updatedAt()),
    ];
}
Migration Pattern
Use enum constants for all field names:
Schema::create({Resource}ModelEnum::tableName(), function (Blueprint $table) {
    $table->id();
    $table->string({Resource}ModelEnum::title());
    $table->boolean({Resource}ModelEnum::isCompleted())->nullable()->default(false);
    $table->timestamps();
});
Routes
• Use Route::apiResource() for RESTful resources
• Routes file: routes/api.php
Key Principles
1. No hardcoded strings - all field names, table names must come from enums
2. BaseModel required - all models must extend BaseModel, not Model directly
3. Separation of concerns - controllers delegate to services
4. Single responsibility - services are single-action classes
5. Consistency - use enum methods everywhere
6. Type safety - use proper type hints and return types
7. API responses - use camelCase for client-facing fields
8. Database fields - use snake_case in database and backend code
Example Flow
When creating a new resource module:
1. Create enum with all field definitions and helper methods
2. Create migration using enum constants
3. Create model extending BaseModel (not Model) with modelEnum() method
4. Create form requests (Post/Put) extending BaseFormRequest with enum-based rules
5. Create services (Create/Update) with handle() method
6. Create API resource using enum methods, returning camelCase
7. Create controller with dependency injection
8. Add route using apiResource
Critical: Always ensure models extend BaseModel and implement the modelEnum() method. Never create models that extend Model directly or have their own constructor that sets table/fillable.Always follow these patterns exactly. Never deviate from the enum-based approach, BaseModel pattern, or hardcode string literals.
